{"id":"2206.10921","submitter":"Li-Yong Zhou","authors":"Yang-Bo Xu (1), Li-Yong Zhou (1), Hejiu Hui (2), Jian-Yang Li (3) ((1)\n  School of Astronomy and Space Science, Nanjing University, (2) School of\n  Earth Sciences and Engineering, Nanjing University, (3) Planetary Science\n  Institute, USA)","title":"The diurnal Yarkovsky effect of irregularly shaped asteroids","comments":"Accepted by Astronomy & Astrophysics, 11 pages, 12 figures","journal-ref":"A&A 666, A65 (2022)","doi":"10.1051/0004-6361/202243049","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.EP","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The Yarkovsky effect plays an important role in the motions of small\ncelestial bodies. Increasingly improving observations bring the need of\nhigh-accuracy modelling of the effect. Using a multiphysics software COMSOL, we\nmodel the diurnal Yarkovsky effect in three dimensions and compare the results\nwith that derived from the widely adopted theoretical linear model. We find\nthat the linear model presents a high accuracy for spherical asteroids in most\ncases. The ranges of parameters in which the relative error of the linear model\nis over 10\\% are explored. For biaxial ellipsoidal asteroids (particularly\noblate ones), the linear model systematically overestimates the transverse\nYarkovsky force by $\\sim$10\\%. The diurnal effect on triaxial ellipsoids is\nperiodic for which no linear model is available. Our numerical calculations\nshow that the average effects on triaxial ellipsoids are stronger than that on\nbiaxial ellipsoids. We also investigate the diurnal effect on asteroids of real\nshapes and find it be overestimated by the linear model averagely by 16\\%, with\na maximum up to 35\\%. To estimate the strength of Yarkovsky effect directly\nfrom the shape, we introduce a quantity \"effective area\" for asteroids of any\nshapes, and find a significant linear relationship between the Yarkovsky\nmigration rate and the effective area. This brings great convenience to the\nestimation in practice.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 22 Jun 2022 09:01:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-12"}
